      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u explain how lift actually works on a wing? like i know bernoulli is involved but i dont really get the connection between the shape of the airfoil and the actual pressure difference",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, lift on a wing is a bit like a clever trick played by the air. When air flows over the wing, it has to travel faster over the curved top surface and slower underneath because of the wing's shape, which is called an airfoil. This difference in speed creates a pressure difference, with lower pressure on top and higher pressure below, thanks to Bernoulli's principle. The wing essentially uses this pressure difference to \"suck\" itself up, like a clever little goblin lifting a heavy stone with a magic spell. The shape of the airfoil is crucial to this trick, as it ensures that the air flows in just the right way to create the necessary pressure difference.",
