      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait what do you mean by a goblin? i was just asking about the physics. can you just explain the pressure difference part again without the metaphors? like how does the air actually behave differently over the top?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. Let's dive straight into the physics without the goblin analogy. When air flows over a wing, it has to travel a longer path over the curved upper surface compared to the shorter path underneath. According to Bernoulli's principle, as the speed of the air increases, the pressure decreases. So, the faster-moving air over the top of the wing creates a region of lower pressure compared to the slower-moving air beneath the wing. This pressure difference between the top and bottom surfaces of the wing generates an upward force, which we perceive as lift. The shape of the airfoil is designed to maximize this pressure difference and therefore maximize lift.",
      "source": "target",
